---
export const prerender = false;

import ToolPageLayout from '../../../layouts/ToolPageLayout.astro';
import { P2PShare } from '../../../components/P2PShare';

const { roomId } = Astro.params;

const faqs = [
  {
    question: "What is P2P file sharing and how does it work?",
    answer: "Peer-to-Peer (P2P) file sharing is a decentralized networking technology that allows devices to share digital files directly with each other without uploading them to a central cloud server. In a WebRTC-based P2P connection, the sender's browser reads the file and streams it in binary chunks directly to the receiver's browser, bypassing intermediate storage entirely."
  },
  {
    question: "What is WebRTC file transfer?",
    answer: "WebRTC (Web Real-Time Communication) is an open-source standard that enables real-time peer-to-peer data channels between browsers. In file sharing, WebRTC uses the <code>RTCDataChannel</code> API to establish a direct, bidirectional binary data tunnel, allowing files to be sent directly from one device to another without installing any external software or browser plugins."
  },
  {
    question: "Is WebRTC file transfer secure?",
    answer: "Yes, WebRTC is highly secure. It mandates end-to-end encryption for all media and data channels using Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) and Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP). Because the file data is streamed directly between your devices and never stored on intermediate servers, it remains completely protected from third-party interception."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the maximum file size limit for WebRTC transfers?",
    answer: "Technically, WebRTC has no hard file size limits because data is sent as a continuous stream of binary packets. However, because browsers compile the incoming packets in the receiver's temporary system memory (RAM) buffer before saving, transfers are limited by the receiver's available RAM. For the best experience, we recommend files up to 1GB."
  },
  {
    question: "Where are my files stored during a P2P transfer?",
    answer: "Files are not stored anywhere on the internet. They reside only on the sender's and receiver's local devices. During transfer, the file is read into the sender browser's memory sandbox, transmitted directly over the encrypted WebRTC connection, and written directly into the receiver's browser memory before being downloaded to their local storage."
  },
  {
    question: "Can I close the browser tab during a P2P transfer?",
    answer: "No. Since the file transfer is active peer-to-peer and streams directly between the two browser sandboxes, closing either the sender or receiver tab will terminate the connection immediately. Both browsers must remain open and active until the transfer reaches 100% completion."
  },
  {
    question: "Why is my WebRTC connection failing or stuck at 'Connecting'?",
    answer: "This is usually caused by firewalls or strict symmetric NAT configurations (common on guest Wi-Fi networks or corporate office networks) blocking direct IP routing. When this happens, browsers cannot establish a direct WebRTC connection. Switching both devices to a standard cellular hotspot or the same local Wi-Fi network will usually resolve this."
  },
  {
    question: "Can I resume a paused or interrupted WebRTC file transfer?",
    answer: "No. Because our P2P file share tool works entirely in-memory in the browser for maximum privacy and does not write temporary files to a server, we do not support transfer resumption. If the connection drops, both parties must re-establish the connection and restart the transfer from the beginning."
  },
  {
    question: "Is WebRTC file transfer faster than cloud uploads?",
    answer: "Yes. Traditional cloud storage requires you to upload the file to a server at your upload speed, and then the recipient downloads it at their download speed, doubling the time. WebRTC starts transferring immediately, and if both devices are on the same local Wi-Fi or LAN, speeds can reach the maximum limits of your local hardware, bypassing internet upload caps."
  },
  {
    question: "Does WebRTC file sharing work without an internet connection?",
    answer: "WebRTC requires an active internet connection initially to communicate with a temporary signaling server to coordinates the initial handshake (exchanging SDP connection offers and ICE network candidates). Once the direct peer-to-peer connection is established, the transfer runs locally, meaning it will continue even if external internet access is lost, provided the devices remain on the same local network."
  }
];
---

<ToolPageLayout
  title="Receive File Privately: Secure P2P WebRTC Transfer"
  description="Receive files directly inside your browser over an encrypted, peer-to-peer WebRTC data channel with zero server retention or transit logs."
  keywords="p2p file sharing, receive files directly, secure file transfer, private file sharing online, webrtc receiver"
  noindex={true}
  toolTitle="P2P File Share"
  toolDescription="Secure, client-side peer-to-peer file sharing. Your files are encrypted in transit and streamed directly between browsers using WebRTC with zero server storage."
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <P2PShare client:only="react" roomId={roomId} />

  <!-- Detailed SEO articles about receiving P2P WebRTC file transfers -->
  <div slot="seo-content" class="flex flex-col gap-8">
    <!-- Section: Intro -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 tracking-tight mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="w-1.5 h-6 bg-accent-emerald rounded-full"></span>
        Receiving Files Safely Point-to-Point
      </h2>
      <p class="text-zinc-400 text-sm leading-relaxed font-sans mb-4">
        You have accessed a secure, direct file transfer room. When you load this page, your browser automatically connects to a temporary signaling server to coordinates a WebRTC handshake with the sender.
      </p>
      <p class="text-zinc-400 text-sm leading-relaxed font-sans">
        Once the connection is established, the sender will read the file and stream it directly into your browser using standard, secure datagram tunnels. Absolutely zero data goes to a server, and the file is compiled dynamically inside your local browser memory sandbox.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</ToolPageLayout>
